  Oh that's a really interesting use case. That's called **environment comparison** or **cross-environment NRT**.

---

## What She Means

Instead of comparing actual response against a static `expected-response.json` file —

```
Normal NRT:
Actual response (UAT)  vs  expected-response.json (static file)
```

You compare **two live environments against each other:**

```
Cross-env NRT:
Actual response (DEV)  vs  Actual response (PROD)
```

---

## Why This Is Powerful

Real scenario:

> "We deployed a fix to DEV. Does DEV now return the same thing as PROD?"

Or:

> "Before we deploy to PROD, does UAT match PROD exactly?"

You're not comparing against a hardcoded expected value. You're comparing two live systems in real time.

---

## How It Would Work

```
Engine fires same request to DEV
          ↓
Engine fires same request to PROD
          ↓
Compares both responses
          ↓
Any difference = regression flagged
```

Workflow would take two URLs as input:

```yaml
inputs:
  env1_url:
    description: 'First environment (e.g. DEV)'
  env2_url:
    description: 'Second environment (e.g. PROD)'
  auth_token_env1:
    description: 'Token for env1'
  auth_token_env2:
    description: 'Token for env2'
```

---

